text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Mayo%0a%0a:Author: victorwa%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThe endangered language of Mayo%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aMayo is an Uzo-Aztecan language, spoken by around 40,000 Mexican Mayo, or Yoreme Indians, who reside in the Mexican state of Sonora as well as the neighboring state of Sinaloa. It is recognized as a national language along with 62 other indigenous languages along with Spanish in Mexico. The endangerment of this language is caused by the widespread adoption of English and Spanish in schools, as they are perceived as more practical in business and to improve one's income. Due to this, the support for these languages being taught in schools have outstripped support for indigenous languages. Additionally, lack of education among the general public of these indigenous languages have put those who spoke these indigenous languages such as Mayo in a socioeconomic disadvantage. They aren't able to communicate with others well if only few people know the language. In terms of revitalization efforts, the Mexican government has promoted the preservation of indigenous languages through a branch of the Ministry of Culture called "Inali", where virtual comics, books, and other resources were created to expose hundreds of thousands of people to these endangered indigenous languages, including Mayo. Unfortunately, these efforts do not translate well into the classroom or into actual learning, which limits proficiency of these languages, and it may just be a waste of effort. %0aEthnologue shows that the EGIDS level of Mayo is 6b-9, meaning that it is endangered, and that children no longer learn and use the language as the norm.%0a%0ahttps://mexiconewsdaily.com/opinion/the-fight-to-save-mexicos-native-languages/%0a%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayo_language%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 221204-040344-622860#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!68 Voices, 68 hearts covered this language! %0a-> - dani26%0a-> [-03.12.2022 - 20:03-]%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a{[foxdelrange button 221204-040344-622860 {$FullName} ]}%0a(:if1end:)%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PbzaUMrab6E%0aThe 68 voices, 68 hearts project is a series of animated short films that tell indigenous stories using their own languages! I thought it's a really good example of helping revitalize languages -- making media in them broadly and conveniently accessible through appealing formats like shorts. %0ahttps://www.cinematropical.com/cinema-tropical/watch-mexican-indigenous-tales-in-their-native-language-in-68-voices-68-hearts (information in English)%0a%0a%0ahttps://68voces.mx/mayo-el-origen-del-fuego (video information)%0a%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 221204-040344-622860#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:S